The Maryland Department of the Environment (MDE) recently issued a general permit to address discharges from swimming pools and spas.
"This permit authorizes the discharge of pool or spa overflows, drainage, cleaning wastewater and filter backwash," said Robert Summers, director of MDE's Water Management Administration.
"These effluents often have the potential to cause localized problems in the receiving waters.
The permit requires quality control of wastewater by the best available treatment or pollution prevention technology."
Pool owners are required to obtain permits for discharges from all "public" pools (including private marinas) to surface water, ground water or storm sewers.
Pool owners discharging only to sanitary sewers are not required to register under this permit.
They must receive permission to discharge from the operator of the sanitary sewer and meet any conditions that operator imposes, however.
Pool owners must submit a Notice of Intent to MDE along with the required filing fee of $100.
For additional information, contact Patsy Allen at MDE: 410631-3634 or pallen@mde.state.md.us.
