UNDERW SUMMER 2002 Maryland Clean Marinas AY "Bay Game" Promotes Clean Boating Every year, 300,000 Maryland Bay Games are distributed to motorists traveling over the William Preston Lane, Jr.
Memorial Bridge (Bay Bridge) on their way to the ocean.
Designed for children ages 3 and up, the Bay Game helps increase awareness of how our surroundings relate to the Chesapeake Bay.
The 24 page booklet chronicles the adventures of two water droplets as they travel through the Chesapeake Bay watershed.
The booklet includes a word search, crossword puzzle, math quiz, secret code message, a stump-the-grownups game, and a full page of color stickers.
It also encourages children to locate 14 sites which are marked with "Bay Game Site" highway signs on the way to the beach.
One of these signs overlooks Lippincott Marine in Grasonville.
The corresponding text in the Maryland Bay Game describes how certified Clean Marinas safeguard Maryland's air and water and help boaters do the same.
For example, "One partner in protection, Lippincott Marine, uses vacuum sanders to remove paint from boat bottoms, keeping toxic dust off the ground and out of the Bay."
The text further encourages kids and their parents to follow clean boating tips and directs them to DNR's web site for a complete list of certified Clean Marinas.
Requests for copies of the Bay Game should be sent to mdbaygameorder@dnr.state.md.us or to: A.V. Grant, Bay Game Manager Maryland Department of Natural Resources 580 Taylor Ave., D4 Annapolis, MD 21401 Please include your organization's name, mailing address, phone number and the number of games requested.
BMP Spotlight: Environmental Precautions at the Fuel Dock The height of the boating season is here and with it is the potential for accidental spills at fuel docks.
While most spills are smalla matter of ouncesthe cumulative result can be devastating .
A recent report from the National Research Council indicates that toxic compounds found in petroleum may have adverse effects on marine species even at very low concentrations.* To protect our waterways and to help your customers avoid hefty fines, follow these guidelines for environmentallyresponsible fuel dock operations: Ã¯Â¿Â½ Always have a trained employee at the fuel dock to oversee fueling .
Ã¯Â¿Â½ Ask the employee to clarify the product the customer has asked for.
For example, "Here is gasoline, Captain.
You asked for gasoline."
Also, ask the employee to note that the customer is using the proper intake: not the access port to the holding tank or a fishing rod holder! Ã¯Â¿Â½ Have the employee hand each customer an oil absorbent pad and/or a no-spill jug to capture backsplash and vent line overflow.
Keep separate pads for diesel and gasoline.
Store them in plastic buckets at the fuel dock.
Once diesel pads are saturated, double bag them and place in your regular trash.
Allow gasoline pads to air dry and reuse indefinitely.
Fuel captured in a no-spill jug can be offered to the next customer or used in marina equipment such as lawn mowers.
Ã¯Â¿Â½ Remove holding clips from fuel nozzles.
They are illegal at marina fuel docks (COMAR 26.10.01.20E and 26.10.03.07).
Also, remind boaters that soda cans or other devices may not be used to hold nozzles open.
Ã¯Â¿Â½ Instruct fuel dock personnel and boaters to listen to fill pipes to anticipate when tanks are nearly full.
Ã¯Â¿Â½ Instruct boaters to slow down at the beginning and end of fueling .
Ã¯Â¿Â½ Encourage boaters to fill their tanks just before leaving on a trip to reduce spillage due to thermal expansion and rocking , i.e., if fuel is used before it warms up, it cannot spill overboard.
Ã¯Â¿Â½ If boaters prefer to refuel upon their return to port, encourage them to fill their tanks to no more than 90 percent of capacity.
Ã¯Â¿Â½ Suggest to customers who routinely vent fuel overboard that they install fuel/air separators along their vent lines to prevent such overflows.
