Your Input Needed on State Boating Expenditures 2 Funding Available to control SAV at Public Facilities 2 Congressional Staffers Tour Shipwright Harbor Marina 2 Three New Clean Marinas 3 New Flags Accentuate Clean Marinas 3 New Pool Permit Affects Marinas 4 1 I NPUT N EEDED ON W ATERWAY I MPROVEMENT F UND F INANCIAL ASSISTANCE AVAILABLE TO CONTROL NUISANCE The Maryland Department of Natural Resources is undertaking a study to 1) assess the condition and use of existing boating infrastructure, e.g ., ramps, marinas, channels, 2) assess environmental and other constraints on new development, and 3) recommend procedures for linking funding decisions to identified needs while being mindful of environmental constraints and linkages to broad policy goals such as the Chesapeake Bay Agreement.
The first stage of the study is a survey of public and private marina and boat launch operators.
The surveys will be mailed in mid-June.
Later in the summer, 1,500 registered boaters will be surveyed to gather information about their boating habits and their perceptions of where infrastructure needs to be improved or, conversely, pristine areas that should not be developed.
Ultimately, the results will be used to refine how Waterway Improvement Funds (WIF) are distributed.
The WIF was established in 1966 to benefit the general boating public by funding projects to improve and promote recreational and commercial capabilities, conditions, and safety of Maryland's waterways.
Revenues for the fund are obtained primarily from the one time excise tax that is paid to the State when a boat is purchased and titled in the State.
The fund also receives a small percentage of the state motor fuel tax.
Depending upon Congressional reauthorization of the Boating Infrastructure Grant program, the study results will also guide allocation of Maryland's share of these federal funds.
Every boating facility operator in Maryland should receive a copy of the survey.
The time it takes to complete the survey will be well worth the effort.
Don't miss this opportunity to help define State policy with regard to publicly-funded waterway improvements.
For additional information, contact Beth Fuller Valentine at 410-260-8776 or bvalentine@dnr.state.md.us.
SAV AT PUBLIC FACILITIES Three New Certified Clean facilities have Marinas Three In many tidal areas of the Chesapeake Bay, submerged aquatic vegetation (SAV) populations are increasing .
As distribution grows, conflicts between boaters and nuisance aquatic plants can be expected to increase.
In areas where SAV is abundant, boat ramps can become clogged with plants to the point where it is difficult or even impossible to reach open water from launching and docking areas.
Navigational impediments have been a persistent problem in the Potomac River since hydrilla appeared in the early 1980s, which resulted in the formation of the MD/VA/DC Council of Governments Hydrilla Control Program.
As hydrilla continues to spread throughout the Chesapeake, the group anticipates user conflicts on a broader scale.
To minimize conflicts and maintain open channels, the Department of Natural Resources plans to establish a mechanism for control of nuisance aquatic plants throughout the tidal waters of Maryland wherever water access from public facilities is restricted.
Efforts will seek both to open channels from point-to-point and to completely eradicate species at low abundance that pose great threats (e.g ., water chestnut).
For the summer of 2002, DNR has set up a program to provide financial assistance to public boating facilities that experience problems with water access due to SAV growth.
This summer, a permitting system will be established similar to what exists for dredging projects, wherein public facility operators will submit written requests to the Department for SAV control.
Control efforts will involve physically cutting SAV beds above the sediment and removing plant materials to an off-site location.
To better anticipate the scale of problems to be expected this summer, anyone who has had problems in the past is asked to call or e-mail Mike Naylor of MD DNR at mnaylor@dnr.state.md.us or 410-260-8652.
