The tour was designed to stress the importance of continued NOAA funding to state Coastal Programs and to try to redress a cap on current funding levels.
BMP Spotlight (continued from page 1) been certified as Clean Marinas since the last issue of Underway was published.
The newest additions to the list of premier marinas in Maryland are Bay Boat Works in North East, Gratitude Marina in Rock Hall, and Skipjack Landing Marine Center in Chester.
"Everybody, staff and customers, worked so hard to achieve this award," said Bay Boat Works vice president Mary Green.
"We are so proud that an older facility like ours has been recognized for upholding high environmental standards related to our operations which include vessel maintenance, a fuel dock, a sewage pumpout system, slip rentals, and winter storage."
Ms. Green runs the marina along with her husband Donald Green whose grandfather started the business in 1928.
The marina is located on 31.7 acres of property, more than 20 acres of which is undeveloped marsh land.
The facility Don and Mary Green, Bay Boat is distinguished by a collection of outbuildings that span the marina's history.
For instance, the carpentry Works, with their Clean Marina shop was used to build munition boxes during World War II.
Award.
Gratitude Marina is a working boat yard with 80 wet slips and room to store 225 boats on land in the winter.
While marina staff use the usual precautions of vacuum sanders and tenting vessels that are to be sand- or soda-blasted, general manager Jon Wright insists that educating customers to use pollution prevention measures can have a large impact on the quality of Bay waters as well.
"Boatyards can lead by example, setting good practices for customers to see and imitate.
In this way, we can all help to reverse the effects of past practices that put the Bay in jeopardy."
Skipjack Landing Marine Center is a working boat yard with about 60 slips and an emphasis on engine repair and maintenance.
Owner Ralph Kirchner collects and recycles used oil, John Diver (L) and Jon Wright (R), Gratitude antifreeze and gasoline.
Additionally, all used solvents are collected by a hazardous waste Marina, with their Clean Marina Award. hauler.
"We protect our waterways by maintaining a neat shop," said Mr. Kirchner.
His wife, Karen Kirchner, added, "We also require customers who perform their own vessel maintenance to abide by our pollution prevention policies.
For instance, any hull sanding must be conducted over filter fabric or with a vacuum sander."
There are now a total of 41 certified Clean Marinas in Maryland and 8 Clean Marina Partners.
An additional 97 facilities have pledged to meet the Clean Marina criteria.
As reported in the last issue of Under way , Mark and Kim Kahan, Fairview Marina, recently earned the Clean Marina Award.
Clean Marinas now enjoy even greater visibility.
Each certified Clean Marina has been presented with a 3' x 5' flag in the State colors emblazoned with the Clean Marina logo and the slogan, "Partners in Protection" (see picture on page 4 of this newsletter).
The eye-catching flags make it easier for boaters to identify certified Clean Marinas.
Certified facility operators may order additional flags for $37 each by sending a check made out to the Department of Natural Resources to the Clean Marina office.
NEW FLAGS A CCENTUATE CERTIFIED CLEAN MARINAS Congressional Staffers Tour Shipwright Harbor Marina John Meneely, owner of Shipwright Harbor Marina in Deale, led a tour of his certified Clean Marina for federal representatives on May 29, 2002.
The group included staff from the Coastal States Organization and the offices of U.S. Congressional Representatives Loretta Sanches (D -CA), Frank Pallone (D-NJ), and Sam Farr (D - CA).
Mr. Meneely highlighted pollution prevention measures, including a grant-funded wash water recycling system and oil and antifreeze recycling tanks.
Managers of neighboring Clean Marinas, Herrington Harbor North and Rockhold Creek Marina, also joined the tour to offer their impressions of the Clean Marina Initiative and their customers' positive reactions to this voluntary program to protect Maryland's waterways.
The stop at Shipwright Harbor was part of a day-long tour for members of the "U.S. Coastal Caucus," NOAA appropriations subcommittee, and natural resources subcommittee to become C Ã¯Â¿Â½ Post signs summarizing your fuel dock rules.
A sign will lend credibility to the dock hand who is trying , for example, to get a reluctant boater to use an oil absorbent pad.
A sign allows a dock hand to respectfully and authoritatively request that the customer follow the marina rules.
